To find the rank of the matrix A, we need to perform Gaussian elimination to find the row echelon form of the matrix, and then count the number of non-zero rows.

Matrix A:
\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 4 & 6 \\ 1 & 3 & 5 \\ 7 & 8 & 9 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Step 1: Swap Row 1 and Row 2 to get a 1 in the top left corner:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 5 \\ 2 & 4 & 6 \\ 7 & 8 & 9 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Step 2: Subtract 2 * Row 1 from Row 2:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 5 \\ 0 & -2 & -4 \\ 7 & 8 & 9 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Step 3: Subtract 7 * Row 1 from Row 3:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 5 \\ 0 & -2 & -4 \\ 0 & -13 & -26 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Step 4: Multiply Row 2 by -1/2:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 5 \\ 0 & 1 & 2 \\ 0 & -13 & -26 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Step 5: Add 3 * Row 2 to Row 1:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \\ 0 & 1 & 2 \\ 0 & -13 & -26 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Step 6: Add 13 * Row 2 to Row 3:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \\ 0 & 1 & 2 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\ \end{bmatrix}

Now the matrix is in row echelon form. We can see that there are two non-zero rows, so the rank of matrix A is 2.
